04411nam a22007335i 9781501724152DE-B159720190920094934.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190920s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017241527 a10.7591/97815017241522doi  a(DE-B1597)514777  a(OCoLC)1083586634  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0130002bisacsh1 aFowler, Edward, eauthor.10aSan'ya Blues :bLaboring Life in Contemporary Tokyo /cEdward Fowler. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource :b12 halftones, 5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tMAPS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tA NOTE ON LANGUAGE AND MONEY -- tPROLOGUE -- t1. SETTING -- t2. LIVES -- t3. ACTIVISM -- t4. RITES -- t5. WORK -- tINTERVIEWING. MEMORY AS ORAL HISTORY -- tGLOSSARY -- tGENERAL INDEX -- tINDEX OF PSEUDONYMS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the years, Edward Fowler, an American academic, became a familiar presence in San'ya, a run-down neighborhood in northeastern Tokyo. The city's largest day-labor market, notorious for its population of casual laborers, drunks, gamblers, and vagrants, has been home for more than half a century to anywhere from five to fifteen thousand men who cluster in the mornings at a crossroads called Namidabashi (Bridge of Tears) in hopes of getting work. The day-labor market, along with gambling and prostitution, is run by Japan's organized crime syndicates, the yakuza. Working as a day laborer himself, Fowler kept a diary of his experiences. He also talked with day laborers and local merchants, union leaders and bureaucrats, gangsters and missionaries. The resulting oral histories, juxtaposed with Fowler's narrative and diary entries, bring to life a community on the margins of contemporary Japan.Located near a former outcaste neighborhood, on what was once a public execution ground, San'ya shows a hidden face of Japan and contradicts the common assumption of economic and social homogeneity. Fowler argues that differences in ethnicity and class, normally suppressed in mainstream Japanese society, are conspicuous in San'ya and similar communities. San'ya's largely middle-aged, male day-laborer population contains many individuals displaced by Japan's economic success, including migrants from village communities, castoffs from restructuring industries, and foreign workers from Korea and China. The neighborhood and its inhabitants serve as an economic buffer zone-they are the last to feel the effects of a boom and the first to feel a recession. They come alive in this book, telling urgent stories that personify such abstractions as the costs of modernization and the meaning of physical labor in postindustrial society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aDay laborerszJapanzTokyo. 0aWorking classzJapanzTokyo. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501724152423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501724152.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG